Here's how to save and restore draft text across backgrounding using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NotesViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NotesViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NotesViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NotesViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

### 3. Restore on first launch too

Load any previously saved draft in your ViewModel constructor so it survives app termination:

```csharp
public class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    private string _draftText;

    public NotesViewModel()
    {
        _draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set => SetProperty(ref _draftText, value);
    }
}
```

### Key things to know

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **`Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch** | Initial sequence is `Created → Activated`, so load saved state in the ViewModel constructor too. |
| **Android back-button skips `Stopped`** | It jumps straight to `Destroying`, so save in both `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying`. |
| **Keep handlers fast** | Android enforces ~5s ANR timeout. `Preferences` is fast; avoid DB writes here. |
| **`Deactivated` ≠ `Stopped`** | A notification shade pull-down fires `Deactivated` but the app isn't backgrounded — don't save there. |
